DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
This domain addresses whether resources should be donated now or invested
for later giving—a critical tension between present and future obligations
in utilitarian philanthropy. The debate centers on three core issues: (1) the
philosophical justification for time preference and temporal discounting in
utilitarian calculations; (2) empirical questions about expected returns from
giving now versus investing; and (3) the role of uncertainty and option value
in timing decisions.

Foundational work on intergenerational ethics and time discounting (Ramsey,
Sidgwick, Pigou) provides the classical utilitarian framework that treats
temporal location as morally irrelevant—the "zero time preference" view.
This view has been challenged on both ethical grounds (Heath argues for
positive social time preference; Preston Greene defends time neutralism)
and practical grounds (Greaves surveys discounting in public policy; Stern
and Zuber & Fleurbaey analyze intergenerational welfare economics).

The effective altruism movement revived these debates through the concept
of "patient philanthropy" (Trammell). If investment returns compound faster
than the opportunity cost of delay, deferred giving could multiply impact
dramatically. However, this conflicts with the "hinge of history" hypothesis
(Ord, MacAskill & Greaves) that the present moment may be uniquely pivotal.
The debate extends to practical giving norms: MacAskill, Mogensen, and Ord
propose income-based tithing as a demanding but achievable standard, while
Madoff & Soskis explore temporal considerations in philanthropic structures
more broadly.

Recent work examines how uncertainty affects timing: option value arguments
suggest that preserving flexibility by waiting can be rational even if
expected returns favor immediate giving. This connects directly to whether
asset-holding (with intent to give later) satisfies the same moral
obligations as income-based giving now.

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
This domain is essential to the research question of income-based versus
asset-based giving norms. If patient philanthropy is justified, then
holding assets with intent to give later could be morally equivalent to
or even superior to giving from income now. The literature on time
preference reveals whether the temporal dimension of assets (as deferred
giving) creates distinct moral obligations compared to income flows.

NOTABLE_GAPS:
While the literature extensively debates the ethics of discounting future
benefits, there is surprisingly little work on the ethics of discounting
future obligations. Most patient philanthropy arguments focus on maximizing
impact, not on whether timing affects when obligations are discharged.
Additionally, few papers address how uncertainty about one's own future
wealth or charitable intentions should affect the give-now versus give-later
calculation.

SYNTHESIS_GUIDANCE:
The synthesis should distinguish three levels of analysis: (1) pure time
preference (is temporal location per se morally relevant?); (2) investment
returns and compounding (do practical considerations favor delay?); and
(3) uncertainty and option value (how should we act under radical
uncertainty about the future?). This domain reveals that the case for
asset-based norms depends heavily on empirical claims about investment
returns and philosophical claims about our epistemic access to future needs.

KEY_POSITIONS:
- Time neutralism (0% pure discounting): 4 papers - Classical utilitarian
  view that temporal location is morally irrelevant (Ramsey, Sidgwick,
  Greaves, Preston Greene)
- Positive time preference justification: 3 papers - Arguments that some
  discounting is ethically warranted (Heath, Stern, Zuber & Fleurbaey)
- Patient philanthropy: 5 papers - Case for investing to give later
  (Trammell, Founders Pledge, EA Forum discussions)
- Hinge of history: 3 papers - Present is uniquely important, favoring
  giving now (Ord, MacAskill & Greaves on longtermism, Mogensen replies)
====================================================================
}

