  RELEVANCE: Clarifies the philosophical foundations of time neutralism, which underlies much effective altruist thinking about patient philanthropy. Greene's defense is important for asset-based versus income-based norms because it suggests that temporal location per se should not affect the weight of moral obligations. If temporal location is morally arbitrary, then obligations to use assets for future giving are just as strong as obligations to give from current income—the timing does not reduce the obligation. However, this does not yet tell us whether we should give now or later; it only establishes that pure temporal location is not a reason to favor either.

  POSITION: Philosophical defense of time neutralism; response to permissivism about time bias.
  },
  keywords = {time-neutralism, time-bias, pure-time-preference, Medium}
}

@article{greaves2022longtermism,
  author = {Greaves, Hilary and MacAskill, William},
  title = {The Case for Strong Longtermism},
