  RELEVANCE: Clarifies what is morally at stake in debates about time preference, with implications for patient philanthropy and giving norms. The separation of impartiality from priority helps explain why longtermists (high impartiality) and egalitarians (high priority) can disagree about discounting. For income-versus-assets norms, this suggests the question is not just about temporal impartiality but about inequality: if future people will be richer, priority-based reasoning might favor giving to present poor over investing for future rich, even if impartiality holds. This complicates Trammell's case for patient philanthropy.

